Extplorer

Target IP: 192.168.182.16

Scanning


There are two TCP ports open on the target machine: SSH and HTTP.

Enumeration

Port 80: HTTP

Running gobuster dir -u http://192.168.182.16/ -w /usr/share/wordlists/dirb/big.txt -x php,txt,html shows the interesting directories and files above.


The /filemanager is interesting. The webpage above is displayed for /filemanager. When trying default credential admin:admin, I gained access to the application -- wtf? It looks like the default username and password has not been changed. A message box is shown saying I have privileged account. Another message box is also displayed that contains the two users: admin and dora. The second user is interesting.

Exploitation


After logging in, I notice the contents in /images directory can be accessed without logging in. Therefore, I uploaded my PHP Pentest Monkey reverse shell script here.


And now I have a reverse shell connection from the target machine on port 21. In the picture above, the terminal on top is where I activate the reverse shell connection; whereas the bottom terminal shows the foothold gained from the reverse shell connection.

Privilege Escalation


There is an interesting file called .htusers.php at /var/www/html/filemanager/config. This file contains the bcrypt password hash for the user dora. I copied this has to my local machine and used john to crack the hash!


I obtained the password doraemon for the user dora.


Using the credential dora:doraemon worked! I switched to the user dora. Running id shows this user is a member of disk group; meaning this user can read privileged files.



I obtained the password hash from /etc/shadow of the user root and saved it on my machine. Time to crack the password of the user root.



And now I have the password of the user root using the password explorer.

Flags


The local.txt flag once I escalated my privileges to the user dora.


The proof.txt flag once cracked the password of root and switched user to root.
